{"vocabInfos":[{"lsjDefs":"<b> τέρπω</b>, <br /> [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Odyssea Homerus Epicus “Odyssey” 1.347, etc.\">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]; <i>Epic dialect</i> <i>subjunctive</i> τέρπῃσι [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 17.385 \">Refs</a>]: <i>Ionic dialect</i> <i>imperfect</i> τέρπεσκον [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 4th c.AD(?): Quintus Smyrnaeus Epicus 7.378, “Anthologia Graeca” 9.136 (from Cyrus)\">Refs 4th c.AD+</a>]: <i>future</i> τέρψω [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Sophocles Tragicus “Trachiniae” 1246, etc.\">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]: <i>aorist</i> ἔτερψα [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" “hymnus ad Panem” 47, 5th c.BC: Euripides Tragicus “Heraclidae” 433, 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Leges” 658b:\">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>] —the <i>passive</i> and <i>middle</i> have a fivefold <i>aorist</i>, <br /><Level3><b>__1</b></Level3> ἐτέρφθην [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Odyssea Homerus Epicus “Odyssey” 5.74, 8.131, 17.174, 5th c.BC: Sophocles Tragicus “Oedipus Coloneus” 1140, 5th c.BC: Euripides Tragicus “Ion” 541 (troch.)\">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]; rare in Prose, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th-6th c.BC: Xenophon Historicus “Memorabilia” 2.1.24. \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level3><b>__2</b></Level3> _Epic dialect_ ἐτάρφθην, τάρφθην, 8th c.BC: Odyssea Homerus Epicus “Odyssey” 6.99, 19.213, 251, 21.57. <br /><Level3><b>__3</b></Level3> _Epic dialect_ ἐτάρπην, τάρπην, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\"23.300, 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 11.780, +others\">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]; <i>infinitive</i> ταρπῆναι [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Odyssea Homerus Epicus “Odyssey” 23.212, and ταρπήμεναι [prev. work] 346, 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 24.3; \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]<i>subjunctive</i> τρᾰπείω, <i>Epic dialect</i> <i>1st pers.</i> <i>plural</i> τρᾰπείομεν (see. below [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 11.2). \">Refs</a>]<br /><Level3><b>__4</b></Level3> <i>Epic dialect</i> also ἐταρπόμην, only in <i>1st pers.</i> <i>plural</i> <i>subjunctive</i> ταρπώμεθα [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Odyssea Homerus Epicus “Odyssey” 4.295, +others\">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]; also <i>reduplicate</i> through all moods, τετάρπετο [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 19.19, 24.513; τεταρπώμεσθα 8th c.BC: Odyssea Homerus Epicus “Odyssey” 11.212, 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 23.10, 98; τεταρπόμενος 8th c.BC: Odyssea Homerus Epicus “Odyssey” 1.310, +others \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level3><b>__5</b></Level3> <i>aorist 1</i> ἐτερψάμην, in <i>Epic dialect</i> <i>subjunctive</i> τέρψομαι [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 16.26 (but τέρψομαι\">Refs</a>] is <i>future</i> <i>middle</i> in [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 20.23, 5th c.BC: Sophocles Tragicus “Fragmenta” 677); _optative_ τέρψαιτο “hymnus ad Apollinem” 153 \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]; <i>participle</i> τερψάμενος [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Odyssea Homerus Epicus “Odyssey” 12.188 \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]:—<b>delight, gladden, cheer</b>, ὅ κεν τέρπῃσιν ἀείδων [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 17.385; τῇ [φόρμιγγι] ὅ γε θυμὸν ἔτερπεν 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 9.189, +others; πεσσοῖσι.. θυμὸν ἔτερπον 8th c.BC: Odyssea Homerus Epicus “Odyssey” 1.107; καὶ τὸν ἔτερπε λόγοις 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 15.393; τοὐμὸν.. τ. κέαρ 5th c.BC: Sophocles Tragicus “Trachiniae” 1246 \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]; θοίνῃ σε τ. [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Achaeus Tragicus 17 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; ἡ ἀγγελίη.. ἔτερψε [αὐτούς] [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Herodotus Historicus 8.99 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; sometimes in <i>Attic dialect</i> Prose, ἔπεσι.. τὸ αὐτίκα τέρψει <b>will give</b> momentary <b>pleasure</b>, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Thucydides Historicus 2.41, compare 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Leges” 658b, 658e, etc.\">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; τ. τὴν ἀκοήν, τὰς ἀκοάς, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 1st c.BC: Philodemus Philosophus “περὶ ποιημάτων” 5.26, 28 \">Refs 1st c.BC+</a>]; ἧλιξ τέρπει τὸν ἥλικα, proverbial in [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Phaedrus” 240c, etc.\">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]: <i>absolutely</i>, <b>give delight</b>, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Odyssea Homerus Epicus “Odyssey” 1.347, 8.45, 5th c.BC: Sophocles Tragicus “Ajax” 475 \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]; τὰ τέρποντα <b>delights</b>, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" [prev. author] “OC” 1217 (Lyric poetry)\">Refs</a>]; ῥήματα τέρψαντά τι[<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" [prev. work] 1281; οἱ τέρποντες λόγῳ ῥήτορες 5th c.BC: Thucydides Historicus 3.40; τὰ τέρψοντα 5th-6th c.BC: Xenophon Historicus “Agesilaus” 9.4. \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level2><b>__II</b></Level2> more frequently in <i>passive</i> and <i>middle</i>, <br /><Level3><b>__II.1</b></Level3> in <i>Epic dialect</i> the <i>aorist</i> <i>passive</i> is used, with <i>genitive</i> <i>of things</i>, <b>have full enjoyment of, enjoy to one's heart's content</b>, ἐπεὶ τάρπημεν ἐδητύος ἠδὲ ποτῆτος [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 11.780; ἐπεὶ τάρπησαν ἐδωδῆς 8th c.BC: Odyssea Homerus Epicus “Odyssey” 3.70; σίτου τάρφθεν 6.99; τεταρπόμενοι φίλον ἦτορ σίτου καὶ οἴνοιο 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 9.705 \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]; ὕπνου, εὐνῆς ταρπήμεναι,[<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 24.3, 8th c.BC: Odyssea Homerus Epicus “Odyssey” 23.346; φιλότητος ἐταρπήτην [prev. work] 300; ἥβης ταρπῆναι [prev. work] 212 \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]: <i>metaphorically</i>, <b>take one's fill</b> of lamentation, τεταρπώμεσθα γόοιο [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 23.10, 98, 8th c.BC: Odyssea Homerus Epicus “Odyssey” 11.212, compare 19.213, 21.57. \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level3><b>__II.2</b></Level3> <b>enjoy</b> or <b>delight oneself</b>, with <i>dative</i> <i>instrumental</i>, φρένα τ. φόρμιγγι [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 9.186; μύθοισι 8th c.BC: Odyssea Homerus Epicus “Odyssey” 23.301; δαιτί 1.26; γόῳ φρένα 4.102; δίσκοισιν 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 2.774; ἐν θαλίῃς 8th c.BC: Odyssea Homerus Epicus “Odyssey” 11.603, 8th-7th c.BC: Hesiodus Epicus “Opera et Dies” 115 \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]; φιλότητι (or ἐν φ.) τραπείομεν εὐνηθέντε [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 3.441, 14.314 (whereas in the phrase λέκτρονδε τραπείομεν εὐνηθέντες (variant{-θέντε}), 8th c.BC: Odyssea Homerus Epicus “Odyssey” 8.292, the form τραπείομεν seems to be taken by the poet as belonging to τρέπω, though others retain the usually sense by connecting λέκτρονδε with εὐνηθέντες or by punctuating after λέκτρονδε)\">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]; so in Trag., λαμπάδι τερπόμεναι [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 4th-5th c.BC: Aeschylus Tragicus “Eumenides” 1042 (Lyric poetry), compare 5th c.BC: Sophocles Tragicus “Oedipus Coloneus” 1140, etc.\">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; <b>delight in</b>, τῇ τῶν πυραμίδων μεγαλειότητι [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" “OGI” 666.26 (Egypt, 1st c.AD)\">Refs 1st c.AD+</a>]; τοῖς εὐώδεσι [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 2nd c.AD: Soranus Medicus 2.29; ἐπί τισι 5th c.BC: Euripides Tragicus “Rhesus” 194 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]: with <i>participle</i>, λόγοις.. οἷς σὺ μὴ τέρψῃ κλύων [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Sophocles Tragicus “Antigone” 691; τέρπεται τιμώμενος 5th c.BC: Euripides Tragicus “Bacchae” 321 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; τί ἂν.. ἀκούσας τερφθείη; [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th-6th c.BC: Xenophon Historicus “Memorabilia” 2.1.24: _absolutely_, πῖνε καὶ τέρπευ\">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>] drink and <b>be merry</b>, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Herodotus Historicus 2.78. \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level3><b>__II.3</b></Level3> with internal <i>accusative</i>, οἴην μοῖραν δέκα μοιρέων τέρπεται ἀνήρ <b>has</b> only one tenth part <b>of the enjoyment</b>, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th-7th c.BC: Hesiodus Epicus “Fragmenta” 162; κενὴν ἐτερπόμην.. τέρψιν 5th c.BC: Sophocles Tragicus “Fragmenta” 577; τέρπου κενὴν ὄνησιν 5th c.BC: Euripides Tragicus “Orestes” 1043. \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level3><b>__II.4</b></Level3> frequently with words which limit its sense, θυμῷ [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 19.313, 8th c.BC: Odyssea Homerus Epicus “Odyssey” 16.26; θυμόν 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 21.45; κατὰ θυμόν 8th-7th c.BC: Hesiodus Epicus “Opera et Dies” 58, 358; φρένα 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 1.474, 8th c.BC: Odyssea Homerus Epicus “Odyssey” 4.102, etc.; φρεσὶν ᾗσι τετάρπετο 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 19.19, compare 8th c.BC: Odyssea Homerus Epicus “Odyssey” 5.74; ἐνὶ φρεσίν 8.368; τεταρπόμενος φίλον κῆρ 1.310; ἀπάταισι θυμὸν τέρπεται 5th c.BC: Pindarus Lyricus “P.” 2.74 \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]. (Cf. Sanskrit <i>trpnoti</i> 'take one's fill', Causative <b>tarpáyati</b> 'delight (<i>transitive</i>)', Opruss. <b>ka enterpo.. </b>? 'what is the use of..?', Gothic <i>paurfts</i>, O[<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Euripides Tragicus \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]<b>pearf</b> 'benefit', Gothic <i>parf</i> 'I need'.)","strongNumber":"G9425","accentedUnicode":"τέρπω","shortDef":"to delight; make happy","mediumDef":"to delight; make happy","stepGloss":"to delight","stepTransliteration":"terpō","_step_Type":"verb"}]}